entry.title: Clean up kConsistencyNewAccountInterface
entry.content:
The feature was enabled by default in M122

(https://crrev.com/c/4894113). The diff is big but most of it is file

deletion.



Context: Some time ago, feed folks wanted to implement a sign-in

promo but the UI provided by the sign-in team did not support users

with 0 device-level accounts. The feed team initially implemented their

own homegrown UI, called a "sync half sheet". Later, the sign-in team

added support for the 0-account case, gated behind

kConsistencyNewAccountInterface. The homegrown UI is now removed.



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAMS=FeedSignInPromoCoordinator was removed, along with its metrics. The UI that replaced it has its own set of metrics, e.g. Signin.SignIn.Completed and Signin.SignIn.Started.

undesired & error-prone to allow these feature flags to be checked

entry.title: [//media] Use single NV12 GMB w/software video on Linux by default
entry.content:
This CL changes Linux to use a single NV12 GMB for software video decode

by default when multiplanar SI is enabled. This will switch impacted

users who are currently using either an R8/RG88 pair of hardware GMBs

or an R8 HW GMB/RG88 SW GMB pair to using either a HW NV12 GMB or a SW

NV12 GMB depending on whether their system has support for NV12 native

buffers.



UMA stats indicate that the % of video frame decodes that currently

happen on Linux with hardware-backed dual-GMB compared to

software-backed dual-GMB is ~0.007% (obtained by dividing the total

count of NV12 in OutputFormatHardwareGmb by that in

OutputFormatSoftwareGmb [1]). Since this change will impact only those

VideoFrame decodes, we do not expect it to have any significant

impact on overall performance on Linux.



Computation for stats as of March 13 2024:



55509241 / 783121677991 * 100 = 0.007088



[1] https://uma.googleplex.com/p/chrome/timeline_v2?sid=9f9d9c7106ecc47083179c265ef19632

entry.title: Adapt PlusAddressTable API for sync purposes
entry.content:
Updates and deletions for plus addresses can be issued through sync.

This CL changes the existing PlusAddressTable::AddPlusProfile() to

AddOrUpdatePlusProfile(), and adds a RemovePlusProfile() function.



It shouldn't be necessary to distinguish between adds and updates,

since:

- Distinctions between adds/updates in sync are generally vague (e.g.

what if the add fails due to an I/O error and later an update for

this entity is received?).

- Creating new plus profiles will be communicated to the backend

outside of sync, since PLUS_ADDRESS is read-only. Thus, there can

be a race condition between sync syncing this addition down to the

client and Chrome adding it to the database itself. Handling this

gracefully is desirable.



Bug: b/322147254

entry.title: [win] Only try to remove appcompat flags on browser start
entry.content:
Chrome will attempt to remove appcompat flags during startup. Restrict

this to only browser startups to reduce overhead when starting child

procs. One would hope that removing them once during browser start would

suffice to have them gone for subsequent child process launches, as well

as the next browser launch.



The actual removal now takes place on a background thread sometime after

browser startup, and records whether or not any layers were removed in

Windows.AppCompatLayersRemoved.



This reverts https://crrev.com/1218347 and removes the

NoAppCompatClearInChildren feature.

entry.title: Retrieve info about the fonts from desired family using AppKit
entry.content:
CoreText's approach for retrieving all system fonts from desired family

is working much slower than AppKits `availableMembersOfFontFamily`. This

caused several performance regressions, compare issue

chromium:328483352.



This CL introduces a workaround solution that uses AppKit's

`availableMembersOfFontFamily` to retrieve the information about the

fonts of the desired family and then use CoreText to find the best

weight and trait match. It also introduces a runtime flag for enabling

the current approach that does not use AppKit API for font family

matching.

entry.title: [//media] Eliminate handling of legacy mailboxes in 1c upload to GL
entry.content:
This CL upgrades the DUMP_WILL_BE_CHECK() that source legacy mailboxes

are not supplied to UploadVideoFrameToGLTexture() to a CHECK(). There

have been no problems due to the rollout of this DUMP_WILL_BE_CHECK()

in 123, and more importantly, it is not possible for VideoFrames holding

legacy mailboxes to be supplied to this function:



* This function's only entrypoint is from

CopyVideoFrameTexturesToGLTexture(), and that entrypoint is

conditional on the mailbox either having more than one texture or

holding a multiplanar SharedImage [1].



VideoFrames holding legacy mailboxes can have only one texture:



* The legacy mailbox must ultimately come from here [2], as this is

the only creation of legacy mailboxes that could go into VideoFrames

in the codebase

* That legacy mailbox gets put into a VideoFrame here [3], where the

code makes it self-evidently clear that the VideoFrame will have only

one texture



Additionally, by definition VideoFrames holding legacy mailboxes are not

holding multiplanar SharedImages (the SharedImageFormatType on the

VideoFrame will be Legacy).



As this was the last remaining condition in which 1-copy upload via

legacy mailboxes would be used, this CL also eliminates that codepath

\o/. We leave broader cleanup for followup CLs.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:media/renderers/paint_canvas_video_renderer.cc;l=1495-1504;drc=c292340f0c721cd88f9b14c453c877c55d13ce6b;bpv=1;bpt=1

entry.title: [//gpu] Fix SharedImageInterfaceInProcess ClientSI creation
entry.content:
SharedImageInterfaceInProcess creates ClientSharedImage instances that

are backed by GMBs, and thus it needs to specify the GMB handle type so

that ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget() operates correctly. Creation

of ClientSharedImage for a given plane also needs to be passed the

default value for the `gmb_type` parameter, this CL also makes that

parameter non-optional to avoid any future clients mistakenly not

passing the value.

entry.title: iwa: Integrate with `WebAppManagement` and `WebappInstallSource`
entry.content:
Until now, all IWAs were installed with an install source of

`WebappInstallSource::ISOLATED_APP_DEV_INSTALL`. This CL fixes this by

introducing the following new IWA-specific `WebappInstallSource`s:

- `IWA_SHIMLESS_RMA`

- `IWA_EXTERNAL_POLICY`

- `IWA_GRAPHICAL_INSTALLER`

- `IWA_DEV_UI`

- `IWA_DEV_COMMAND_LINE` (renamed from `ISOLATED_APP_DEV_INSTALL`)



Also, all IWAs used `WebAppManagement::Type::kCommandLine` (which was

introduced specifically for IWAs) as their source of management. This

has caused issues like policy-installed IWAs being uninstallable by the

user. We fix this by introducing:

- `WebAppManagement::Type::kIwaShimlessRma`: IWAs installed in shimless

RMA are neither installed by the user nor by policy - rather, they are

installed by the shimless RMA system. Therefore, it makes sense to

have a separate management type for them.

- `WebAppManagement::Type::kIwaPolicy`: This is similar to `kPolicy`. We

cannot re-use `kPolicy` for IWAs, since policy-installed IWAs are

managed by the `IsolatedWebAppPolicyManager` and not the

`WebAppPolicyManager`.

- `WebAppManagement::Type::kIwaUserInstalled`: This is similar to

`kSync`, but since IWAs are not synced, we make it a separate value.

This also include dev mode IWAs, i.e., IWAs that the user has installed

via command line or dev mode UI.



We remove `WebAppManagement::Type::kCommandLine` without replacement. We

add only `WebAppManagement::Type::kIwaUserInstalled` to the source types

that are user-uninstallable.



For `apps::InstallReason`, we do not introduce IWA-specific types, but

instead re-use the existing types where possible:

- `WebAppManagement::Type::kIwaShimlessRma` is mapped to

`apps::InstallReason::kSystem`

- `WebAppManagement::Type::kIwaPolicy` is mapped to

`apps::InstallReason::kPolicy`

- `WebAppManagement::Type::kIwaUserInstalled` is mapped to

`apps::InstallReason::kUser`



I would've liked to also remove `apps::InstallReason::kCommandLine`, but

was unsuccessful due to the use of the `ENUM` macro to create the enum,

which does not support assigning explicit values to enum members AFAICT.



We add a new `WebApp::IsIwaPolicyInstalledApp` method similar to the

existing `WebApp::IsPolicyInstalledApp` method. I think there is

potential for developers expecting `IsPolicyInstalledApp` to return

`true` for _both_ policy-installed IWAs and PWAs. Therefore I propose to

rename `WebApp::IsPolicyInstalledApp` to

`WebApp::IsPwaPolicyInstalledApp` in a follow-up CL.
